        "title": "Fix Linux OpenCode Go and Command Code usage",
        "body": "## Summary\n- enable OpenCode Go local SQLite usage on Linux through a system SQLite module\n- allow Command Code billing on Linux when a manual cookie is configured\n- carry Command Code cookie settings into CLI snapshots and document Linux source behavior\n- stage the checksum-pinned SQLite header and archive together for static musl release builds\n- add Linux SQLite, source-gating, settings, and strategy regressions\n\nFixes #1657.\n\n## Proof\nExact head: `9a1b1cf97e8a272867e8ee862b5187537c1b63aa`\n\n- `swift test --filter 'CLIEntryTests|TokenAccountEnvironmentPrecedenceTests|CommandCodeProviderTests|OpenCodeGoProviderStrategyTests|OpenCodeGoLinuxTests'` (prior head: 62 passed; exact head focused source-gate and 3 Linux SQLite tests passed)\n- `swift test --filter CommandCodeUsageFetcherTests` (20 passed on prior code-identical provider head)\n- `make check` passed; SwiftFormat clean and SwiftLint reported zero violations\n- `make test` passed all 41 groups / 490 selections on the exact head\n- Release CLI workflow YAML parses locally\n- local musl-staging autoreview clean (0.86); exact full-branch autoreview clean (0.82)\n- Crabbox Linux / Swift 6.2.1 release build on code-identical pre-rebase head `89522516`: OpenCode Go read a real SQLite fixture and returned `source: local`; Command Code with a configured invalid cookie reached the live API and returned invalid-session rather than macOS/browser gating\n- exact manual Release CLI workflow, including both musl matrix builds: pending\n\nThe musl build now installs `sqlite3.h` from the same checksum-verified amalgamation directory used to compile `sqlite3.c` and archive `libsqlite3.a`, before Swift imports the `CSQLite3` shim.\n",
